attributes.background:
The proposal is for the development of a rail-to-road freight Interchange to comprise 5 huge warehouses covering area of 300 acres south of St Albans on the last piece of Green Belt between St Albans and London.

The list of the most devastating of the negative effects if this project goes ahead:
Destruction of Green Belt as concept and as a fact between London and St Albans;
Unacceptable incremental road traffic and as a result, congestion to local roads;
Sharp increase in noise and air pollution in the area;
Huge impact on local community and the way of life of local people;
The intrusive visual impact of a development of this scale in a historic area of national importance.

The list of reasons why the project is viewed as ill conceived, despite assertions of the prospective developer Helioslough:
Lack of available local workforce;
Lack of capacity for rail freight on the Midland Main Line; 
Availability of other sites, which would be much more appropriate and have the support of their local communities;
Hidden intention of Helioslough to use the Interchange as road-to-road Interchange.
